    "instruction": "Load metric.csv, trace.csv, log.csv, and error_logs.csv (parse timestamp column into UTC datetimes). For each file, return a compact summary with these fields: file_name, row_count, min_timestamp_utc, max_timestamp_utc, unique_cmdb_ids (list), and unique_metric_names_with_counts (for metric.csv use kpi_name; for trace.csv use trace_name; for log.csv use log_name; for error_logs.csv return top 20 distinct message samples). Limit each list to at most 50 items. Present counts for each metric/trace/log name. Do not print full raw tables—only the requested aggregates." }

{
    "analysis": "From the prior summary: metric.csv (8582 rows) / trace.csv (9944 rows) / log.csv (1902 rows) are present and cover timestamps from 2024-01-24 06:16:00 to 2024-01-24 06:40:00 UTC, which overlaps the incident window 2024-01-24 06:13:26 to 2024-01-24 06:43:26 UTC. error_logs.csv is empty. Next we must follow the preprocess -> anomaly detection -> fault identification -> localization workflow. The immediate next required step is to compute global thresholds for each component-KPI time series (using the full available series for each component) for the candidate root-cause services (ts-auth-service, ts-order-service, ts-route-service, ts-train-service, ts-travel-service), then extract incident-window points and detect anomalies (points exceeding the global thresholds). This will narrow candidate components and KPIs for further trace/log analysis. No metric-level aggregation or threshold calculation has yet been done for these specific candidate services.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Load metric.csv and parse timestamp with pd.to_datetime(..., unit='s', utc=True). Restrict analysis to the five candidate services: ['ts-auth-service','ts-order-service','ts-route-service','ts-train-service','ts-travel-service']. For metric rows whose cmdb_id is one of these five, aggregate by (cmdb_id, kpi_name) across the full available time series (do NOT filter by incident window for threshold calc). For each (cmdb_id, kpi_name) compute: count, min, max, mean, p50, p90, p95, p99 of value. Then filter the same metric rows to the incident window 2024-01-24 06:13:26 UTC to 2024-01-24 06:43:26 UTC and for each (cmdb_id, kpi_name) compute: incident_count, incident_min, incident_max, incident_mean, number_of_points_exceeding_p95 (use p95 computed from full series), earliest_timestamp_utc_of_point_exceeding_p95 (if any). Return a compact table with one row per (cmdb_id, kpi_name) containing: cmdb_id, kpi_name, full_count, p95, p90, p50, incident_count, incident_max, incident_mean, anomalies_count (>=p95), earliest_anomaly_ts_utc. Limit output rows to at most 50. Also include a short list of which of the five candidate services were actually present in metric.csv. Ensure all timestamps in outputs are UTC datetimes." }

{
    "analysis": "From the previous Executor run we have a metrics-level aggregate (result_df) for the five candidate services. Observations: (1) All five candidate services appear in metric.csv. (2) There are 36 (cmdb_id, kpi_name) series in total (each full_count = 25 samples), and many series show anomalies_count = 2 (i.e., two points during the incident exceeded their full-series P95). (3) Earliest anomaly timestamps appear as early as 2024-01-24 06:16:00 UTC (e.g., ts-auth-service diskio) and other earliest anomalies at 06:18, 06:19, etc., so anomalies are spread across the incident window. (4) Because many series across multiple services show P95 breaches, we cannot conclude the root cause yet; we need to rank these breaches by severity and check whether faults are sustained (consecutive breaches) to identify true faults vs isolated spikes. According to the diagnosis workflow, the next step is to quantify breach severity and detect consecutive-breach runs per series (within the incident window) to find the most significant faults that could be root cause candidates. Traces and logs will be used after narrowing candidates by metrics.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using the existing metric dataframe and the previously computed full-series P95 for each (cmdb_id,kpi_name), restrict metric data to the incident window 2024-01-24 06:13:26 UTC — 2024-01-24 06:43:26 UTC. For each (cmdb_id,kpi_name) that has at least one value >= its full-series P95 inside the incident window, compute: cmdb_id, kpi_name, p95, incident_count (number of points in incident window), anomalies_count (number of points >= p95), incident_max, incident_mean, severity_ratio = incident_max / p95, earliest_anomaly_ts_utc (first timestamp in incident window where value >= p95), longest_consecutive_anomaly_run (maximum number of consecutive incident-window minutes where value >= p95). Return a compact table with these columns, limited to the top 20 rows sorted by severity_ratio descending. Also return a small summary: total number of series with anomalies and per-service counts of series with anomalies (service, series_with_anomalies_count). Ensure all timestamps are in UTC datetimes." }

{
    "analysis": "From metric analysis we observed that all five candidate services (ts-auth-service, ts-order-service, ts-route-service, ts-train-service, ts-travel-service) have multiple (cmdb_id,kpi_name) series that exceeded their full-series P95 during the incident window. Many breaches are small (severity ratios ~1.03–1.36) except two special cases: a diskio spike for ts-route-service (severity ~2.30) and an 'error' series for ts-travel-service where p95==0 produced an infinite severity (but incident_max==0 as well, indicating this metric may be all zeros and not informative). Because multiple service-level components show anomalies, we must use traces next to identify which faulty service is the most downstream faulty service in observed call chains. Traces will help distinguish propagated anomalies from the root cause service. Therefore the next step is targeted trace analysis for the candidate services to find which service trace features show the most significant, sustained deviations during the incident window.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Load trace.csv and parse timestamp with pd.to_datetime(..., unit='s', utc=True). Restrict to rows whose cmdb_id is one of the five candidate services ['ts-auth-service','ts-order-service','ts-route-service','ts-train-service','ts-travel-service'] (include 'root' only if it appears tied to these services). For each (cmdb_id, trace_name) compute the full-series p95 (use all available rows for that series). Then filter the trace rows to the incident window 2024-01-24 06:13:26 UTC — 2024-01-24 06:43:26 UTC. For each (cmdb_id, trace_name) that has at least one value >= its full-series p95 in the incident window, compute: cmdb_id, trace_name, p95, incident_count, anomalies_count (values >= p95), incident_max, incident_mean, severity_ratio = incident_max / p95 (if p95 == 0, mark severity_ratio as 'inf'), earliest_anomaly_ts_utc (first timestamp in incident window where value >= p95), longest_consecutive_anomaly_run (max consecutive minutes within incident window where value >= p95). Return a compact table limited to top 20 rows sorted by severity_ratio descending. Also return a summary with: total number of (cmdb_id,trace_name) series that had >=1 anomaly, and per-service counts of such trace-series (service, series_with_anomalies_count). Ensure all timestamps in outputs are UTC datetimes and keep output rows bounded." }

{
    "analysis": "Trace analysis shows widespread trace error_rate anomalies across many services: many trace error_rate series have full-series p95 == 0 and show anomalies for the entire incident window (25 minutes) starting at ~2024-01-24 06:16:00 UTC. Metric analysis shows multiple services with small-to-moderate KPIs breaches (most severity ratios ~1.03–1.36) and a notable disk I/O spike on ts-route-service (severity ~2.30) at 06:16. Because many services report trace error_rate anomalies simultaneously, we cannot pick the root cause from metrics alone. According to the workflow, we must use traces to map call chains and identify the most downstream service that is actually faulty (i.e., a faulty service at the end of call chains), and use logs to confirm the failure reason (e.g., socket errors, disk I/O, or network issues). The next atomic action is to convert trace anomalies into caller->callee edges to find which downstream services were faulty in calls and their earliest anomaly times.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Load trace.csv and parse timestamp with pd.to_datetime(..., unit='s', utc=True). Compute full-series p95 for each (cmdb_id, trace_name) using all available rows. Filter trace rows to the incident window 2024-01-24 06:13:26 UTC — 2024-01-24 06:43:26 UTC. Identify (cmdb_id, trace_name) series that have >=1 point >= their full-series p95 inside the incident window. For each anomalous trace_name, extract a compact edge record with these fields: trace_name, cmdb_id, p95, anomalies_count (in-window), incident_max, earliest_anomaly_ts_utc, longest_consecutive_anomaly_run, and an inferred edge/call pair parsed from trace_name as 'direction' and 'target_service' where possible (e.g., trace.to_ts-auth-service -> direction='to', target='ts-auth-service'; trace.from_ts-order-service -> direction='from', target='ts-order-service'; trace.from_root -> direction='from_root'). Then aggregate these inferred edges into caller->callee candidate rows: for each 'to' edge, treat caller='cmdb_id' (or 'root' if trace_name contains from_root) and callee=target_service; produce a compact table of caller, callee, total_anomalies_count (sum of anomalies_count), earliest_anomaly_ts_utc (min), and longest_run_max (max of longest_consecutive_anomaly_run). Limit output to top 50 rows sorted by total_anomalies_count desc then earliest_anomaly asc. Also return a short summary listing which services appear as callees with anomalies and their earliest anomaly time and counts (service, earliest_anomaly_ts_utc, total_anomalies_count). Ensure timestamps are UTC datetimes and the output is bounded." }

{
    "analysis": "Trace-edge aggregation shows many caller->callee edges with sustained trace error_rate anomalies beginning ~2024-01-24 06:16:00 UTC and lasting through the incident window. Metric-level analysis narrowed candidate services to the five provided; among metric anomalies the most notable metric-level severity was a disk I/O spike on ts-route-service (severity ~2.30) with earliest anomaly at 2024-01-24 06:16:00 UTC. Many other services show small-to-moderate KPI breaches (severity ratios ~1.03–1.36) during the same period. Traces indicate widespread error_rate anomalies across many services (including our candidate services) at the same start time; this pattern suggests a single, early fault that propagated through the call graph. To distinguish the true root cause and the failure reason, we need log-level evidence and to inspect the ts-route-service diskio time series in the incident window (since that disk I/O spike is both early and relatively large). The next step is log analysis for the candidate services and a focused metric inspection of ts-route-service diskio during the incident window to confirm whether disk I/O is the root cause.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Load log.csv and error_logs.csv and parse timestamps with pd.to_datetime(..., unit='s', utc=True). Restrict log analysis to the five candidate services: ['ts-auth-service','ts-order-service','ts-route-service','ts-train-service','ts-travel-service']. For each (cmdb_id, log_name) compute the full-series p95 using all available rows (do NOT filter by incident window for threshold calc). Then filter log rows to the incident window 2024-01-24 06:13:26 UTC — 2024-01-24 06:43:26 UTC and for each (cmdb_id, log_name) that has at least one value >= its full-series p95 compute: cmdb_id, log_name, p95, incident_count, anomalies_count (>=p95), incident_max, incident_mean, earliest_anomaly_ts_utc. Return a compact table limited to rows with anomalies_count>0, top 20 rows sorted by anomalies_count desc then earliest_anomaly asc. Also return the top 20 distinct messages (samples) from error_logs.csv (if any) with their counts and earliest timestamp; if error_logs.csv is empty, explicitly state that. Separately (still in the same response), inspect metric.csv for the ts-route-service diskio series: compute full-series p95 (if not already known), then filter ts-route-service diskio rows to the incident window and return the incident-window rows as a compact table with columns timestamp_utc and value, limited to top 20 rows, plus a one-line summary of p95, incident_max, earliest_anomaly_ts_utc (first row where value >= p95), and severity_ratio = incident_max / p95 (mark 'inf' if p95==0). Ensure all timestamps are UTC datetimes and outputs are bounded." }

